    <div>

        A bit is the smallest possible unit of data represented by binary. It has a value of either 1 or 0. While it can be used to represent true or false statements, it is often more useful when combined with other bits.
        A good way to write out set of bits is write it out as a binary number grouped in sets of 4 and with 0’s at the front as needed to fill in the extra digits.
        <br />
        <div class="subsection">
            0010 1010
            <sub class="subitle"> A binary number</sub>
        </div>
        <br />
        If dealing with multiple sets of binary numbers, it is a common practice to represent them with the same number of digits even it means adding entire sections of four 0’s at the front.
        <div class="subsection">
            0000 1101
            1111 1212
            <sub class="subitle"> grouping binary numbers</sub>
        </div>
        <br />
        Doing so allows for increased readability and works well when dealing with machines, which typically group everything in set sizes.
        If the number of digits in each number is known ahead of time, one may write multiple numbers in this format on the same line.
        <br />
        <div class="subsection">
            0000 1101 1010 0110 1111 1002 0110 1011
            <sub class="subitle">
                grouping binary numbers on the same line with each number using  8 bits.
            </sub>
        </div>
        <br />
        This reduces readability, but can help show how data is aligned
        <br />
        <br />
        <h3>Grouping bits and bytes</h3>
        <br />
        A nibble is an ordered set of 4 bits. The number of values you can have in a nibble is 24 = 16. It is common to represent a nibble by converting it to a hexadecimal (base 16) number.
        
